seed_articles << {
:title => "Basic Home Brew How To",
:author_name => "Josh B Smith",
:body => <<HERE
Look at the number of different brand names and variations of beer that are now being offered for sale today. Don't forget all of the different types of international beer. You can learn and perfect this system and turn out to be a brew master in your own home.

The process of beer brewing is somewhat straight forward, however developing a great beer definitely requires a large amount of practice. Listed here are the basics of home brewing beer:

1. Sanitation and cleanliness is really essential. Sanitize, sanitize, sanitize. This could not be overemphasized. Carefully wash and sterilize every single component of the fermenting and brewing gear before starting. Bacteria thrives in fermenting beer. This could spoil your beer or simply generate some undesirable flavors. Worst case, it may make you sick.

2. Follow the instructions and measure diligently. Pick the recipe and stick to the instructions and measurements accurately.

3. Mix: In a large cooking pot, boil the wort. At this stage, you can expect to add the hops, moss, and malt, as well as any other ingredients your recipe needs. Always make sure you possess the proper ingredients prior to starting. Almost all recipes call for boiling water as the starting point, followed by the inclusion of some other ingredients. Making use of the proper ingredients in the right amounts, and putting them in the correct order, can make a huge difference to your beer.

4. Cool the wort: Right after you're finished combining and boiling the wort, you will need to cool it quickly. When it's cooling down, your wort could be exposed to undesirable bacteria. Cooling it quickly will help lessen the chance of any undesirable bacteria getting into the wort. Placing the pot in a sink full of cold water can achieve this. After it has cooled off, you can expect to insert the yeast along with any outstanding components. The wort is put right into a fermenting container. It will stay here for a few weeks to ferment. Different kinds of beer require diverse fermenting times as well as temperatures, so make sure to stick to the recipes very carefully.

5. Bottle the beer: As soon as the fermenting process is finished, pour your beer into cleaned and sanitized containers. The beer should stay in these containers for a couple of weeks in order to carbonate as well as condition.

Your home brewed beer should now be ready to consume.

After you have learned the fundamentals of beer making, you'll find it's an easy process that you can excel at in your home. After you have perfected your skills along with your recipes, you will never want to return to commercialized brews ever again.

